<p>In it=E2=80=99s simplest form, this is the formula he presented:</p>



<p><strong><em>Aa + Bb =3D Cc</em></strong></p>



<p>The variables in the formula are probably best described by Mike Miller:=
</p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-style-default is-layout-flow wp-bloc=
k-quote-is-layout-flow"><p>The capital letters&nbsp;<em>A, B, and C</em>&nb=
sp;stand for the specific heats of grain, water, and the mash, respectively=
, and the lower case letters stand for temperatures of the same variables. =
</p><p>What the formula says is that the product of the temperature and spe=
cific heat of a mixture will be equal to the sum of the products of the spe=
cific heat and temperature of the two substances that make up the mixture =
=E2=80=93 in this case, water and grist.</p></blockquote>



<p><strong>A</strong>&nbsp;=3D Heat&nbsp;of grain<br><strong>a</strong>&nbs=
p;=3D Temperature of grain =C2=B0F<br><strong>B</strong>&nbsp;=3D Heat of w=
ater<br><strong>b</strong>&nbsp;=3D Temperature of Water =C2=B0F<br><strong=
>C</strong>&nbsp;=3D Heat of Mash<br><strong>c</strong>&nbsp;=3D Target Tem=
perature of Mash =C2=B0F</p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">For the life of me I can=E2=80=99t i=
magine why Mr. Casey decided to use such confusing terminology&nbsp;<em>(he=
at vs temp),&nbsp;</em>but I promise the formula starts to make much more s=
ense once you apply real world values to the formula. </p>
